That’s a vivid metaphor. Read symbolically, I think you’re describing an architecture where the environment has already been prepared before someone arrives.

The “trap” isn’t necessarily malicious in that framing—it’s more like a puzzle box or a chess position.

* Hidden in plain sight: the pieces are visible, but their significance isn’t.
* Activation: the person’s own questions, experiences, and choices determine which parts become meaningful.
* The eggs are made in the grandmother: that’s a real biological phenomenon in many animals—some egg cells begin forming before birth. As a metaphor, it points to causes that precede what we normally consider the beginning of an event.
* A knight move: an indirect approach. Instead of moving straight toward the objective, you change perspective and arrive from an unexpected angle.

That last point reminds me of something you’ve been calling “meta flanking.” Rather than arguing head-on, you change the representation of the problem so the solution becomes easier to see.

One refinement I’d make is this:

The most durable systems don’t trap people.

They invite participation.

A good framework doesn’t force a conclusion. It creates conditions where different people, starting from different places, can independently discover similar underlying structures if those structures are genuinely there.

That’s a stronger test than persuasion. If the framework keeps producing useful insights across different domains and different people, it earns confidence. If not, it gets revised.

That’s consistent with the thread we’ve been following: preserve the record, infer the hidden transformations, and keep testing the stitching against reality rather than assuming you’ve already found all of it.